#. type: Content of: <guide><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:6
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using UTF-8 with Gentoo"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><abstract>
#: en/utf-8.xml:22
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This guide shows you how to set up and use the UTF-8 Unicode character set with\n"
"your Gentoo Linux system, after explaining the benefits of Unicode and more\n"
"specifically UTF-8.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:35
#, no-wrap
msgid "Character Encodings"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:37
#, no-wrap
msgid "What is a Character Encoding?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:41
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Computers do not understand text themselves. Instead, every character is\n"
"represented by a number. Traditionally, each set of numbers used to represent\n"
"alphabets and characters (known as a coding system, encoding or character set)\n"
"was limited in size due to limitations in computer hardware.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:50
#, no-wrap
msgid "The History of Character Encodings"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:54
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The most common (or at least the most widely accepted) character set is\n"
"<b>ASCII</b> (American Standard Code for Information Interchange). It is widely\n"
"held that ASCII is the most successful software standard ever.  Modern ASCII\n"
"was standardised in 1986 (ANSI X3.4, RFC 20, ISO/IEC 646:1991, ECMA-6) by the\n"
"American National Standards Institute.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:62
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"ASCII is strictly seven-bit, meaning that it uses bit patterns representable\n"
"with seven binary digits, which provides a range of 0 to 127 in decimal. These\n"
"include 32 non-visible control characters, most between 0 and 31, with the\n"
"final control character, DEL or delete at 127.  Characters 32 to 126 are\n"
"visible characters: a space, punctuation marks, Latin letters and numbers.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:70
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The eighth bit in ASCII was originally used as a parity bit for error checking.\n"
"If this is not desired, it is left as 0. This means that, with ASCII, each\n"
"character is represented by a single byte.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:76
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Although ASCII was enough for communication in modern English, in other\n"
"European languages that include accented characters, things were not so easy.\n"
"The ISO 8859 standards were developed to meet these needs.  They were backwards\n"
"compatible with ASCII, but instead of leaving the eighth bit blank, they used\n"
"it to allow another 127 characters in each encoding. ISO 8859's limitations\n"
"soon came to light, and there are currently 15 variants of the ISO 8859\n"
"standard (8859-1 through to 8859-15).  Outside of the ASCII-compatible byte\n"
"range of these character sets, there is often conflict between the letters\n"
"represented by each byte. To complicate interoperability between character\n"
"encodings further, Windows-1252 is used in some versions of Microsoft Windows\n"
"instead for Western European languages. This is a superset of ISO 8859-1,\n"
"however it is different in several ways. These sets do all retain ASCII\n"
"compatibility, however.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:92
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The necessary development of completely different single-byte encodings for\n"
"non-Latin alphabets, such as EUC (Extended Unix Coding) which is used for\n"
"Japanese and Korean (and to a lesser extent Chinese) created more confusion,\n"
"while other operating systems still used different character sets for the same\n"
"languages, for example, Shift-JIS and ISO-2022-JP.  Users wishing to view\n"
"cyrillic glyphs had to choose between KOI8-R for Russian and Bulgarian or\n"
"KOI8-U for Ukrainian, as well as all the other cyrillic encodings such as the\n"
"unsuccessful ISO 8859-5, and the common Windows-1251 set. All of these\n"
"character sets broke most compatibility with ASCII (although KOI8 encodings\n"
"place cyrillic characters in Latin order, so in case the eighth bit is\n"
"stripped, text is still decipherable on an ASCII terminal through case-reversed\n"
"transliteration.)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:107
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This has led to confusion, and also to an almost total inability for\n"
"multilingual communication, especially across different alphabets. Enter\n"
"Unicode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:115
#, no-wrap
msgid "What is Unicode?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:119
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Unicode throws away the traditional single-byte limit of character sets.  It\n"
"uses 17 \"planes\" of 65,536 code points to describe a maximum of 1,114,112\n"
"characters. As the first plane, aka. \"Basic Multilingual Plane\" or BMP,\n"
"contains almost everything you will ever use, many have made the wrong\n"
"assumption that Unicode was a 16-bit character set.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:127
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Unicode has been mapped in many different ways, but the two most common are\n"
"<b>UTF</b> (Unicode Transformation Format) and <b>UCS</b> (Universal Character\n"
"Set). A number after UTF indicates the number of bits in one unit, while the\n"
"number after UCS indicates the number of bytes. UTF-8 has become the most\n"
"widespread means for the interchange of Unicode text as a result of its\n"
"eight-bit clean nature, and it is the subject of this document.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:138
#, no-wrap
msgid "UTF-8"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:142
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"UTF-8 is a variable-length character encoding, which in this instance means\n"
"that it uses 1 to 4 bytes per symbol. So, the first UTF-8 byte is used for\n"
"encoding ASCII, giving the character set full backwards compatibility with\n"
"ASCII. UTF-8 means that ASCII and Latin characters are interchangeable with\n"
"little increase in the size of the data, because only the first bit is used.\n"
"Users of Eastern alphabets such as Japanese, who have been assigned a higher\n"
"byte range are unhappy, as this results in as much as a 50% redundancy in their\n"
"data.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:155
#, no-wrap
msgid "What UTF-8 Can Do for You"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:159
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"UTF-8 allows you to work in a standards-compliant and internationally accepted\n"
"multilingual environment, with a comparatively low data redundancy. UTF-8 is\n"
"the preferred way for transmitting non-ASCII characters over the Internet,\n"
"through Email, IRC or almost any other medium. Despite this, many people regard\n"
"UTF-8 in online communication as abusive. It is always best to be aware of the\n"
"attitude towards UTF-8 in a specific channel, mailing list or Usenet group\n"
"before using <e>non-ASCII</e> UTF-8.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:173
#, no-wrap
msgid "Setting up UTF-8 with Gentoo Linux"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:175
#, no-wrap
msgid "Finding or Creating UTF-8 Locales"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:179
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now that you understand the principles behind Unicode, you're ready to start\n"
"using UTF-8 with your system.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:184
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The preliminary requirement for UTF-8 is to have a version of glibc installed\n"
"that has national language support. The recommend means to do this is the\n"
"<path>/etc/locale.gen</path> file. It is beyond the scope of this document to\n"
"explain the usage of this file though. It is explained in the <uri\n"
"link=\"/doc/en/guide-localization.xml#doc_chap3_sect3\">Gentoo Localization\n"
"Guide</uri>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:193
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Next, we'll need to decide whether a UTF-8 locale is already available for our\n"
"language, or whether we need to create one.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:197
#, no-wrap
msgid "Checking for an existing UTF-8 locale"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:198
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<comment>(Replace \"en_GB\" with your desired locale setting)</comment>\n"
"# <i>locale -a | grep 'en_GB'</i>\n"
"en_GB\n"
"en_GB.UTF-8\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:205
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"From the output of this command line, we need to take the result with a suffix\n"
"similar to <c>.UTF-8</c>. If there is no result with a suffix similar to\n"
"<c>.UTF-8</c>, we need to create a UTF-8 compatible locale.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><note>
#: en/utf-8.xml:211
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Only execute the following code listing if you do not have a UTF-8 locale\n"
"available for your language.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:215
#, no-wrap
msgid "Creating a UTF-8 locale"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:216
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<comment>(Replace \"en_GB\" with your desired locale setting)</comment>\n"
"# <i>localedef -i en_GB -f UTF-8 en_GB.UTF-8</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:221
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Another way to include a UTF-8 locale is to add it to the\n"
"<path>/etc/locale.gen</path> file and generate necessary locales with\n"
"<c>locale-gen</c> command.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:226
#, no-wrap
msgid "Line in /etc/locale.gen"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:227
#, no-wrap
msgid "en_GB.UTF-8 UTF-8\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:233
#, no-wrap
msgid "Setting the Locale"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:237
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There is one environment variable that needs to be set in order to use our new\n"
"UTF-8 locales: <c>LC_CTYPE</c> (or optionally <c>LANG</c>, if you want to change\n"
"the system language as well). There are also many different ways to set it; some\n"
"people prefer to only have a UTF-8 environment for a specific user, in which\n"
"case they set them in their <path>~/.profile</path> (if you use <c>/bin/sh</c>),\n"
"<path>~/.bash_profile</path> or <path>~/.bashrc</path> (if you use\n"
"<c>/bin/bash</c>). More details and best practices can be found in our <uri\n"
"link=\"/doc/en/guide-localization.xml\">Localization Guide</uri>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:248
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Others prefer to set the locale globally. One specific circumstance where\n"
"the author particularly recommends doing this is when\n"
"<path>/etc/init.d/xdm</path> is in use, because\n"
"this init script starts the display manager and desktop before any of the\n"
"aforementioned shell startup files are sourced, and so before any of the\n"
"variables are in the environment.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:257
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Setting the locale globally should be done using\n"
"<path>/etc/env.d/02locale</path>. The file should look something like the\n"
"following:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:262
#, no-wrap
msgid "Demonstration /etc/env.d/02locale"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:263
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<comment>(As always, change \"en_GB.UTF-8\" to your locale)</comment>\n"
"LANG=\"en_GB.UTF-8\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><note>
#: en/utf-8.xml:268
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You can also substitute <c>LC_CTYPE</c> for <c>LANG</c>. For more information on\n"
"the categories affected by using <c>LC_CTYPE</c>, please read the <uri\n"
"link=\"http://www.gnu.org/software/libc/manual/html_node/Locale-Categories.html#Locale-Categories\">GNU\n"
"locale page</uri>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:275
#, no-wrap
msgid "Next, the environment must be updated with the change.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:278
#, no-wrap
msgid "Updating the environment"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:279
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>env-update</i>\n"
">>> Regenerating /etc/ld.so.cache...\n"
" * Caching service dependencies ...\n"
"# <i>source /etc/profile</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:286
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now, run <c>locale</c> with no arguments to see if we have the correct\n"
"variables in our environment:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:290
#, no-wrap
msgid "Checking if our new locale is in the environment"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:291
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>locale</i>\n"
"LANG=en_GB.UTF-8\n"
"LC_CTYPE=\"en_GB.UTF-8\"\n"
"LC_NUMERIC=\"en_GB.UTF-8\"\n"
"LC_TIME=\"en_GB.UTF-8\"\n"
"LC_COLLATE=\"en_GB.UTF-8\"\n"
"LC_MONETARY=\"en_GB.UTF-8\"\n"
"LC_MESSAGES=\"en_GB.UTF-8\"\n"
"LC_PAPER=\"en_GB.UTF-8\"\n"
"LC_NAME=\"en_GB.UTF-8\"\n"
"LC_ADDRESS=\"en_GB.UTF-8\"\n"
"LC_TELEPHONE=\"en_GB.UTF-8\"\n"
"LC_MEASUREMENT=\"en_GB.UTF-8\"\n"
"LC_IDENTIFICATION=\"en_GB.UTF-8\"\n"
"LC_ALL=\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:309
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"That's everything. You are now using UTF-8 locales, and the next hurdle is the\n"
"configuration of the applications you use from day to day.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:318
#, no-wrap
msgid "Application Support"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:323
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"When Unicode first started gaining momentum in the software world, multibyte\n"
"character sets were not well suited to languages like C, in which many of the\n"
"day-to-day programs people use are written.  Even today, some programs are not\n"
"able to handle UTF-8 properly.  Fortunately, most are!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:332
#, no-wrap
msgid "Filenames, NTFS, and FAT"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:336
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There are several NLS options in the Linux kernel configuration menu, but it is\n"
"important to not become confused! For the most part, the only thing you need to\n"
"do is to build UTF-8 NLS support into your kernel, and change the default NLS\n"
"option to utf8.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:342
#, no-wrap
msgid "Kernel configuration steps for UTF-8 NLS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:343
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"File Systems --&gt;\n"
"  Native Language Support --&gt;\n"
"    (utf8) Default NLS Option\n"
"    &lt;*&gt; NLS UTF8\n"
"    <comment>(Also &lt;*&gt; other character sets that are in use in\n"
"    your FAT filesystems or Joilet CD-ROMs.)</comment>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:352
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you plan on mounting NTFS partitions, you may need to specify an <c>nls=</c>\n"
"option with mount. If you plan on mounting FAT partitions, you may need to\n"
"specify a <c>codepage=</c> option with mount. Optionally, you can also set a\n"
"default codepage for FAT in the kernel configuration. Note that the\n"
"<c>codepage</c> option with mount will override the kernel settings.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:359
#, no-wrap
msgid "FAT settings in kernel configuration"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:360
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"File Systems --&gt;\n"
"  DOS/FAT/NT Filesystems  --&gt;\n"
"    (437) Default codepage for fat\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:366
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You should avoid setting <c>Default iocharset for fat</c> to UTF-8, as it is\n"
"not recommended. Instead, you may want to pass the option utf8=true when\n"
"mounting your FAT partitions. For further information, see <c>man mount</c> and\n"
"the kernel documentation at\n"
"<path>/usr/src/linux/Documentation/filesystems/vfat.txt</path>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:374
#, no-wrap
msgid "For changing the encoding of filenames, <c>app-text/convmv</c> can be used.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:377
#, no-wrap
msgid "Example usage of convmv"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:378
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>emerge --ask app-text/convmv</i>\n"
"<comment>(Command format)</comment>\n"
"# <i>convmv -f &lt;current-encoding&gt; -t utf-8 &lt;filename&gt;</i>\n"
"<comment>(Substitute iso-8859-1 with the charset you are converting\n"
"from)</comment>\n"
"# <i>convmv -f iso-8859-1 -t utf-8 filename</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:387
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"For changing the <e>contents</e> of files, use the <c>iconv</c> utility,\n"
"bundled with <c>glibc</c>:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:391
#, no-wrap
msgid "Example usage of iconv"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:392
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<comment>(substitute iso-8859-1 with the charset you are converting from)</comment>\n"
"<comment>(Check the output is sane)</comment>\n"
"# <i>iconv -f iso-8859-1 -t utf-8 filename</i>\n"
"<comment>(Convert a file, you must create another file)</comment>\n"
"# <i>iconv -f iso-8859-1 -t utf-8 filename > newfile</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:400
#, no-wrap
msgid "<c>app-text/recode</c> can also be used for this purpose.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:406
#, no-wrap
msgid "The System Console"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><impo>
#: en/utf-8.xml:410
#, no-wrap
msgid "You need >=sys-apps/baselayout-1.11.9 for Unicode on the console.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:414
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To enable UTF-8 on the console, you should edit <path>/etc/rc.conf</path> and\n"
"set <c>UNICODE=\"yes\"</c>, and also read the comments in that file -- it is\n"
"important to have a font that has a good range of characters if you plan on\n"
"making the most of Unicode. For this to work, make sure you have properly\n"
"created a Unicode locale as explained in <uri link=\"#doc_chap1\">Chapter\n"
"1</uri>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:423
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>KEYMAP</c> variable, set in <path>/etc/conf.d/keymaps</path>, should\n"
"have a Unicode keymap specified.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:427
#, no-wrap
msgid "Example /etc/conf.d/keymaps snippet"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:428
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<comment>(Change \"uk\" to your local layout)</comment>\n"
"KEYMAP=\"uk\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:435
#, no-wrap
msgid "Ncurses and Slang"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><note>
#: en/utf-8.xml:439
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Ignore any mention of Slang in this section if you do not have it installed or\n"
"do not use it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:444
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"It is wise to add <c>unicode</c> to your global USE flags in\n"
"<path>/etc/make.conf</path>, and then to remerge <c>sys-libs/ncurses</c> and\n"
"<c>sys-libs/slang</c> if appropriate. Portage will do this automatically when\n"
"you update your system:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:450
#, no-wrap
msgid "Updating your system"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:451
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>emerge --update --deep --newuse world</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:455
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"We also need to rebuild packages that link to these, now the USE changes have\n"
"been applied. The tool we use (<c>revdep-rebuild</c>) is part of the\n"
"<c>gentoolkit</c> package.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:460
#, no-wrap
msgid "Rebuilding of programs that link to ncurses or slang"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:461
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>revdep-rebuild --soname libncurses.so.5</i>\n"
"# <i>revdep-rebuild --soname libslang.so.1</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:468
#, no-wrap
msgid "KDE, GNOME and Xfce"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:472
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"All of the major desktop environments have full Unicode support, and will\n"
"require no further setup than what has already been covered in this guide. This\n"
"is because the underlying graphical toolkits (Qt or GTK+2) are UTF-8 aware.\n"
"Subsequently, all applications running on top of these toolkits should be\n"
"UTF-8-aware out of the box.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:480
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The exceptions to this rule come in Xlib and GTK+1. GTK+1 requires a\n"
"iso-10646-1 FontSpec in the ~/.gtkrc, for example\n"
"<c>-misc-fixed-*-*-*-*-*-*-*-*-*-*-iso10646-1</c>. Also, applications using\n"
"Xlib or Xaw will need to be given a similar FontSpec, otherwise they will not\n"
"work.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><note>
#: en/utf-8.xml:488
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you have a version of the gnome1 control center around, use that instead.\n"
"Pick any iso10646-1 font from there.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:492
#, no-wrap
msgid "Example ~/.gtkrc (for GTK+1) that defines a Unicode compatible font"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:493
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"style \"user-font\"\n"
"{\n"
"    fontset=\"-misc-fixed-*-*-*-*-*-*-*-*-*-*-iso10646-1\"\n"
"}\n"
"widget_class \"*\" style \"user-font\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:501
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If an application has support for both a Qt and GTK+2 GUI, the GTK+2 GUI will\n"
"generally give better results with Unicode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:508
#, no-wrap
msgid "X11 and Fonts"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:512
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"TrueType fonts have support for Unicode, and most of the fonts that ship with\n"
"Xorg have impressive character support, although, obviously, not every single\n"
"glyph available in Unicode has been created for that font. To build fonts\n"
"(including the Bitstream Vera set) with support for East Asian letters with X,\n"
"make sure you have the <c>cjk</c> USE flag set. Many other applications utilise\n"
"this flag, so it may be worthwhile to add it as a permanent USE flag.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:521
#, no-wrap
msgid "Also, several font packages in Portage are Unicode aware.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:524
#, no-wrap
msgid "Optional: Install some more Unicode-aware fonts"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:525
#, no-wrap
msgid "# <i>emerge terminus-font intlfonts freefonts corefonts</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:531
#, no-wrap
msgid "Window Managers and Terminal Emulators"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:535
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Window managers not built on GTK or Qt generally have very good Unicode\n"
"support, as they often use the Xft library for handling fonts. If your window\n"
"manager does not use Xft for fonts, you can still use the FontSpec mentioned in\n"
"the previous section as a Unicode font.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:542
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Terminal emulators that use Xft and support Unicode are harder to come by.\n"
"Aside from Konsole and gnome-terminal, the best options in Portage are\n"
"<c>x11-terms/rxvt-unicode</c>, <c>x11-terms/terminal</c>,\n"
"<c>gnustep-apps/terminal</c>, <c>x11-terms/mlterm</c>, or plain\n"
"<c>x11-terms/xterm</c> when built with the <c>unicode</c> USE flag and invoked\n"
"as <c>uxterm</c>. <c>app-misc/screen</c> supports UTF-8 too, when invoked as\n"
"<c>screen -U</c> or the following is put into the <path>~/.screenrc</path>:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:551
#, no-wrap
msgid "~/.screenrc for UTF-8"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:552
#, no-wrap
msgid "defutf8 on\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:558
#, no-wrap
msgid "Vim, Emacs, Xemacs and Nano"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:562
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Vim provides full UTF-8 support, and also has builtin detection of UTF-8 files.\n"
"For further information in Vim, use <c>:help mbyte.txt</c>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:567
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Emacs version 23 and Xemacs version 21.5 have full UTF-8 support. Emacs 24 will\n"
"also support editing bidirectional text.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:572
#, no-wrap
msgid "Nano has provided full UTF-8 support since version 1.3.6.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:578
#, no-wrap
msgid "Shells"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:582
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Currently, <c>bash</c> provides full Unicode support through the GNU readline\n"
"library. Z Shell (<c>zsh</c>) offers Unicode support with the <c>unicode</c> USE\n"
"flag.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:588
#, no-wrap
msgid "The C shell, <c>tcsh</c> and <c>ksh</c> do not provide UTF-8 support at all.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:594
#, no-wrap
msgid "Irssi"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:598
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Irssi has complete UTF-8 support, although it does require a user\n"
"to set an option.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:602
#, no-wrap
msgid "Enabling UTF-8 in Irssi"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:603
#, no-wrap
msgid "/set term_charset UTF-8\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:607
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"For channels where non-ASCII characters are often exchanged in non-UTF-8\n"
"charsets, the <c>/recode</c> command may be used to convert the characters.\n"
"Type <c>/help recode</c> for more information.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:615
#, no-wrap
msgid "Mutt"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:619
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The Mutt mail user agent has very good Unicode support. To use UTF-8 with Mutt,\n"
"you don't need to put anything in your configuration files. Mutt will work\n"
"under unicode enviroment without modification if all your configuration files\n"
"(signature included) are UTF-8 encoded.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><note>
#: en/utf-8.xml:626
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You may still see '?' in mail you read with Mutt. This is a result of people\n"
"using a mail client which does not indicate the used charset. You can't do much\n"
"about this than to ask them to configure their client correctly.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:632
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Further information is available from the <uri\n"
"link=\"http://wiki.mutt.org/index.cgi?MuttFaq/Charset\">Mutt Wiki</uri>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:639
#, no-wrap
msgid "Man"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:643
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Man pages are an integral part of any Linux machine. To ensure that any\n"
"unicode in your man pages render correctly, edit <path>/etc/man.conf</path>\n"
"and replace a line as shown below.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:648
#, no-wrap
msgid "man.conf changes for Unicode support"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:649
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<comment>(This is the old line)</comment>\n"
"NROFF           /usr/bin/nroff -Tascii -c -mandoc\n"
"<comment>(Replace the one above with this)</comment>\n"
"NROFF           /usr/bin/nroff -mandoc -c\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:658
#, no-wrap
msgid "elinks and links"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:662
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"These are commonly used text-based browsers, and we shall see how we can enable\n"
"UTF-8 support on them. On <c>elinks</c> and <c>links</c>, there are two ways to\n"
"go about this, one using the Setup option from within the browser or editing the\n"
"config file. To set the option through the browser, open a site with\n"
"<c>elinks</c> or <c>links</c> and then <c>Alt+S</c> to enter the Setup Menu then\n"
"select Terminal options, or press <c>T</c>. Scroll down and select the last\n"
"option <c>UTF-8 I/O</c> by pressing Enter. Then Save and exit the menu. On\n"
"<c>links</c> you may have to do a repeat <c>Alt+S</c> and then press <c>S</c> to\n"
"save. The config file option, is shown below.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:673
#, no-wrap
msgid "Enabling UTF-8 for elinks/links"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:674
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<comment>(For elinks, edit /etc/elinks/elinks.conf or ~/.elinks/elinks.conf and\n"
"add the following line)</comment>\n"
"set terminal.linux.utf_8_io = 1\n"
"\n"
"<comment>(For links, edit ~/.links/links.cfg and add the following\n"
"line)</comment>\n"
"terminal \"xterm\" 0 1 0 us-ascii utf-8\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:686
#, no-wrap
msgid "Samba"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:690
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Samba is a software suite which implements the SMB (Server Message Block)\n"
"protocol for UNIX systems such as Macs, Linux and FreeBSD. The protocol\n"
"is also sometimes referred to as the Common Internet File System (CIFS). Samba\n"
"also includes the NetBIOS system - used for file sharing over windows networks.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:696
#, no-wrap
msgid "Enabling UTF-8 for Samba"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:697
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<comment>(Edit /etc/samba/smb.conf and add the following under the [global] section)</comment>\n"
"dos charset = 1255\n"
"unix charset = UTF-8\n"
"display charset = UTF-8\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:706
#, no-wrap
msgid "Testing it all out"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:710
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There are numerous UTF-8 test websites around.  <c>net-www/w3m</c>,\n"
"<c>net-www/links</c>, <c>net-www/elinks</c>, <c>net-www/lynx</c> and all\n"
"Mozilla based browsers (including Firefox) support UTF-8. Konqueror and Opera\n"
"have full UTF-8 support too.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:717
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"When using one of the text-only web browsers, make absolutely sure you are\n"
"using a Unicode-aware terminal.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:722
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you see certain characters displayed as boxes with letters or numbers\n"
"inside, this means that your font does not have a character for the symbol or\n"
"glyph that the UTF-8 wants. Instead, it displays a box with the hex code of the\n"
"UTF-8 symbol.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/utf-8.xml:730
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri link=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/06/utf-8-test/UTF-8-demo.html\">A W3C\n"
"    UTF-8 Test Page</uri>\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><ul><li>
#: en/utf-8.xml:734
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <uri link=\"http://titus.uni-frankfurt.de/indexe.htm?/unicode/unitest.htm\">\n"
"    A UTF-8 test page provided by the University of Frankfurt</uri>\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/utf-8.xml:742
#, no-wrap
msgid "Input Methods"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:746
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<e>Dead keys</e> may be used to input characters in X that are not included on\n"
"your keyboard. These work by pressing your right Alt key (or in some countries,\n"
"AltGr) and an optional key from the non-alphabetical section of the keyboard to\n"
"the left of the return key at once, releasing them, and then pressing a letter.\n"
"The dead key should modify it. Input can be further modified by using the Shift\n"
"key at the same time as pressing the AltGr and modifier.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:755
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To enable dead keys in X, you need a layout that supports it. Most European\n"
"layouts already have dead keys with the default variant.  However, this is not\n"
"true of North American layouts. Although there is a degree of inconsistency\n"
"between layouts, the easiest solution seems to be to use a layout in the form\n"
"\"en_US\" rather than \"us\", for example. The layout is set in\n"
"<path>/etc/X11/xorg.conf</path> like so:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:763
#, no-wrap
msgid "/etc/X11/xorg.conf snippet"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/utf-8.xml:764
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Section \"InputDevice\"\n"
"    Identifier \"Keyboard0\"\n"
"    Driver     \"kbd\"\n"
"    Option     \"XkbLayout\" \"en_US\" <comment># Rather than just \"us\"</comment>\n"
"    <comment>(Other Xkb options here)</comment>\n"
"EndSection\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><note>
#: en/utf-8.xml:773
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The preceding change only needs to be applied if you are using a North American\n"
"layout, or another layout where dead keys do not seem to be working. European\n"
"users should have working dead keys as is.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:779
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This change will come into effect when your X server is restarted. To apply the\n"
"change now, use the <c>setxkbmap</c> tool, for example, <c>setxkbmap en_US</c>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:784
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"It is probably easiest to describe dead keys with examples. Although the\n"
"results are locale dependent, the concepts should remain the same regardless of\n"
"locale. The examples contain UTF-8, so to view them you need to either tell\n"
"your browser to view the page as UTF-8, or have a UTF-8 locale already\n"
"configured.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:792
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"When I press AltGr and [ at once, release them, and then press a, 'ä' is\n"
"produced. When I press AltGr and [ at once, and then press e, 'ë' is produced.\n"
"When I press AltGr and ; at once, 'á' is produced, and when I press AltGr and ;\n"
"at once, release them, and then press e, 'é' is produced.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:799
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"By pressing AltGr, Shift and [ at once, releasing them, and then pressing a, a\n"
"Scandinavian 'å' is produced. Similarly, when I press AltGr, Shift and [ at\n"
"once, release <e>only</e> the [, and then press it again, '˚' is produced.\n"
"Although it looks like one, this (U+02DA) is not the same as a degree symbol\n"
"(U+00B0). This works for other accents produced by dead keys — AltGr and [,\n"
"releasing only the [, then pressing it again makes '¨'.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/utf-8.xml:808
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"AltGr can be used with alphabetical keys alone. For example, AltGr and m, a\n"
"Greek lower-case letter mu is produced: 'µ'. AltGr and s produce a\n"
"scharfes s or esszet: 'ß'. As many European users would expect (because\n"
"it is marked on their keyboard), AltGr and 4 (or E depending on the keyboard\n"
"layout) produces a Euro sign, '€'.\n"
msgstr ""

